Subject: Re: [EVDL] EVLN: Focus guessometer-overreaction,too-much info
for noob-driver

On 13 Nov 2012 at 17:03, Bruce EVangel Parmenter wrote:

> If we believe that last paragraph, a journalist would have wanted to,
> not so much support EVs, but spend the majority of the piece showing
how
> to over come all the fears other noobs would have.

These days the job of a "journalist" is not to inform the public; it's
to 
attract viewers / listeners / readers who will see / hear the
publication's 
ads.  News today is almost 100% entertainment.  The more controversy and

emotional hand-wringing a story has, the more effective it is at this 
objective.  On no account should the writer ever seriously try to
educate 
the audience - unless it's propaganda the publication's owner wants to 
spread.

But this may not be as big an issue as it seems.  "Journalists" are 
generally poorly educated in technology and science.  However, as I 
understand it, the main paying customers for EVs right now are early 
adopters.  They tend to be well educated, far more so than the 
"journalists."  Many are in technical professions.  

These educated folks are pretty well aware of the limitations of modern 
"journalism," and I'd expect (but don't know for sure) that for unbiased

information they'd look instead to other owners' experiences - probably 
reported on the net.  

Thus I'm not so sure that the negative news pieces are much of an
impediment 
now.  However, they might dampen the growth of the field so that mass 
adoption is slowed down or stopped.

 
> I would have thought (or rather perhaps wanted) all that negative
> EV hoopla would die down after the election. 

I don't think it's much about politics.  It's money.  (But the two often
go 
hand in hand.)

> 
> By Automakers only making EVs have a too-informative display, they
scare
> the noobs away. We need to make it easier for the ice-primates to
learn
> to drive an EV, not scare them away. Later, after a week of driving
> their EV, then they can graduate from noob-mode to normal-mode.
> 

As we saw in early sales of the Prius, well educated early adopters are 
often technically inclined. Thus the assumption seems to have been that
they 
want and expect high-tech instrumentation.  This isn't a new idea; I'm 
pretty sure that the Prius had a touchscreen display before any other
car it 
its price class.

But there may be something to the idea of providing adjustable levels of

display sophistication, so the owner could choose a range of information

from "just the basics" to "almost as distracting as trying to send text 
messages on your mobile phone."  

David Roden - Akron, Ohio, USA
EVDL Administrator

